<%= form_for @conn, admin_invitation_path(@conn, :create), [as: :invitation, multipart: true], fn f -> %>
  <div class="form-group">
    <%= label f, :csv, "CSV file", class: "control-label" %>
    <%= file_input f, :csv %>
  </div>
  <%= submit "Invite", class: "btn btn-primary" %>
<% end %>

<br />
<h2>How to create a CSV file</h2>
To export an excel worksheet as a CSV file, follow the following steps:
<ol>
  <li>Click `File` &gt; `Save as`</li>
  <li>Under file format, select `CSV UFT-8(Comma delimited)`</li>
  <li>Choose the file location</li>
  <li>Click `Save`</li>
</ol>

<h3>Example excel table format:</h3>
<p>Note: That the excel sheet not have any headers</p>
<table class="table table-bordered">
  <tr><th>name</th><th>email</th><th>team</th></tr>
  <tr><td>John</td><td>john@e.ntu.edu.sg</td><td>ateam</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Basil quek</td><td>basil@e.ntu.edu.sg</td><td>bteam</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Example CSV format:</h3>
<p>
  The CSV file should contain 2 columns (name and email):
  <pre>
  name,email,team
  John,john@e.ntu.edu.sg,ateam
  Basil quek,basil@e.ntu.edu.sg,bteam</pre>
  Note that there shouldn't be any spaces inbetween the commas
</p>
